ce:section.ce:para:
RT-qPCR analysis demonstrated a significant enhancement in mRNA expression of VEGF-A by the NC gel with Se.DFO-CQDs 50 % in comparison to control group and the NC gel with Se.DFO-CQDs 0 % (**p < 0.01 and *p < 0.05 respectively) during the first 7 days, however, no significant difference was observed between the NC gel with Se.DFO-CQDs 0 % and control group. Additionally, after 14 days, there was no significant difference in the expression level of VEGF-A among the groups (
                           Fig. 11a
                           ). This could be because angiogenesis happens in the initial phases of wound healing [61]. Based on the results, the considerable enhancement of VEGF-A expression might be due to the presence of Se and DFO in the form of CQD, and also gelatin/alginate-based NC gel. Some studies showed that carbon-based nanostructures like CQDs can accelerate wound healing by stimulating angiogenesis, and antibacterial and antioxidant dual activities [62,63]. Besides, several studies have stated that DFO can stimulate the overexpression of VEGF and angiogenesis through stabilizing and inducing hypoxia inducible factor-1 alpha (HIF-1α) [64]. Similarly, Ding et al. synthesized an injectable DFO-laden silk nanofiber hydrogel and showed this wound dressing can accelerate diabetic wound healing by alleviating of dysangiogenesis and chronic inflammation [64]. Also, Sheng et al. designed an alginate/gelatin hydrogel loaded with adipose-derived mesenchymal stem cells (ASCs) and proved this hydrogel can promote wound repairing through upregulation of VEGF and PDGF, and also decreasing interleukin-1β (IL-1β) and interleukin-6 (IL-6) expression [65].
